@startuml relationships

left to right direction

class A
class B

'dependency is a relationship where one class (the client) depends on another
'class (the supplier) for its functionality. It indicates that the client class
'uses or interacts with the supplier class, but it does not imply any ownership
'or lifecycle management between the classes.

'A ..>  B : depends on

'note on link
'the client class uses the supplier
'class, but it does not imply any
'ownership between the classes.
'end note



'association represents a relationship between two classes where one class uses
'or interacts with another class. It is a more general relationship than
'aggregation or composition, and it does not imply any ownership or lifecycle
'management between the classes.

'A -->  B : association

'note on link
'   it does not imply any ownership
'   or lifecycle management between
'   the classes.
'end note


'aggregation is a special form of association, it represents a "whole-part"
'relationship between the aggregate (whole) and a component part. The aggregate
'is responsible for the lifecycle of the component parts, but the component
'parts can exist independently of the aggregate.

'A o--  B : aggregation

'note on link
'   the component parts can exist
'   independently of the aggregate.
'end note

'composition is a stronger form of aggregation, it represents a "whole-part"
'relationship where the component parts are strongly owned by the aggregate. The
'lifecycle of the component parts is tightly coupled to the lifecycle of the
'aggregate, meaning that if the aggregate is destroyed, the component parts will
'also be destroyed.

'A *--  B : composition

'note on link
'   if the aggregate is destroyed,
'   the component parts will also be
'   destroyed.
'end note

'generalization is a relationship between a more general class (the parent or superclass) and a more specific class (the child or subclass). The child class
'inherits the attributes and behaviors of the parent class, and it can also have
'its own unique attributes and behaviors.

'A <|-- B : generalization

'note on link
'   The child inherits the attributesof
'   the parent, and it can also have
'   its own unique attributes
'end note

@enduml

@startuml mutliple_relationships

left to right direction


class A
class B

'

'using the association relationship btw A and B show all the combination of
'multiplicity
'
A "1" --> "1" B : one-to-one 
A "1" --> "*" B : one-to-many
A "1" --> "0..1" B : one to zero-or-one 
A "1" --> "0..*" B : one to zero-or-many

'A "*" --> "1" B : many-to-one 
'A "*" --> "*" B : many-to-many 
'A "0..1" --> "1" B : zero-or-one to one 
'A "0..1" --> "0..1" B : zero-or-one to zero-or-one 
'A "0..*" --> "1" B : zero-or-many to one 
'A "0..*" --> "0..*" B : zero-or-many to zero-or-many

@enduml

@startuml notas

class A
class B

'direction optionals: left, right, up, down
A -down--> B

note right of A
   This is a note for class A.
   It can span multiple lines.
end note

note bottom of B
   This is a note for class B.
   It can also span multiple lines.
end note

'association with a note
note as extraNote
   extra not as instance
end note
A .. extraNote

@enduml

@startuml attributes
class A {
   == attributes ==
   +publicAttribute: int
   -privateAttribute: string
   #protectedAttribute: float
   == methods ==
   +publicMethod(): void
   -privateMethod(param: int): string
   #protectedMethod(param1: int, param2: string): float
   {static} +staticMethod(): void
}
'note bottom of A
'   == is used to separate sections ==
'
'   : returnType is used to indicate the
'   type of value that a method returns.
'   If a method does not return any
'   value, it can be specified as void
'
'   (param) is used to indicate that
'   the method takes parameters, and
'   the type of each parameter can also
'   be specified.
'end note
@enduml

@startuml relation_matrix


left to right direction

skinparam classAttributeIconSize 0
hide circle

class Base_public {
  +public
  #protected
  -private
}

class Derived_public {
  +public
  #protected
}

class Base_protected {
  +public
  #protected
  -private
}

class Derived_protected {
  #protected
}

class Base_private {
  +public
  #protected
  -private
}

class Derived_private {
  -private
}

Base_public -right[#blue]-> Derived_public : <b><color:blue>public</color></b>
note on link
  public → public
  protected → protected
end note

Base_protected -right[#green]-> Derived_protected : <b><color:green>protected</color></b>
note on link
  public → protected
  protected → protected
end note

Base_private -right[#red]-> Derived_private : <b><color:red>private</color></b>
note on link
  public → private
  protected → private
end note

@enduml

class Base {
   public: int pub;
   protected: int prot;
   private: int priv;
};
class DerivedPublic    : public    Base {
/* pub->public,
   prot->protected,
   priv=hidden */
};
class DerivedProtected : protected Base {
/* pub->protected
   prot->protected
   priv=hidden */
};
class DerivedPrivate   : private   Base {
/* pub->private
   prot->private
   priv=hidden */
};


