@startuml class_tpes
left to right direction

' abstract class — a class that cannot be instantiated directly, only subclassed. Used to define a common base with some methods left unimplemented, forcing derived classes to implement them. Typical use: Shape as abstract, Circle and Square as concrete subclasses.
' interface — a pure contract, no implementation at all. Any class that "implements" it must provide all its methods. Difference from abstract class: a class can implement multiple interfaces but only inherit one abstract class. Typical use: Printable, Serializable, Comparable.
' enum — a fixed set of named constants. Used when a variable can only take one of a predefined set of values. Typical use: Color { RED, GREEN, BLUE }, Direction { NORTH, SOUTH, EAST, WEST }.
' annotation — metadata attached to classes or methods, doesn't affect behavior directly. Mostly a Java concept (@Override, @Deprecated). Rarely drawn in UML unless documenting a Java codebase specifically.
' entity — represents a persistent data object, typically mapped to a database table. Common in JPA/Hibernate Java diagrams. Similar to a class but semantically means "this gets stored in a database".
' exception — a class that represents an error condition. Syntactic sugar in PlantUML — functionally identical to a class but visually signals it's part of the error handling system.
' protocol — a Swift/Objective-C concept, essentially equivalent to interface. Used when documenting iOS/macOS codebases to be semantically precise about the language construct.
' struct — a value type (as opposed to a reference type). In C++ and Swift, structs are copied on assignment instead of passed by reference. Signals that instances are lightweight value objects, not heap-allocated objects.



'class MyClass {
